Case 1, the professor's speech, is better overall. It is more effective both linguistically and non-linguistically. In terms of language, the professor sounds more organized, purposeful, and audience-centered. His speech appears to follow a clear line of development, so listeners can grasp the main idea without confusion. The diction is more formal and appropriate to a public talk, and the delivery seems steadier, which makes the message sound more credible. By contrast, the journalist's speech in Case 2 feels much less controlled. Her wording is more fragmented and hesitant, and the interruptions and self-corrections reduce fluency. As a result, the speech sounds less polished and less persuasive.

From a non-verbal perspective, the professor also performs better. He stands with confidence, uses the stage effectively, and maintains a composed posture. His facial expression and body language suggest authority and calmness, which help him build rapport with the audience. The audience's attention also seems stable, showing that he can hold the room. In Case 2, however, the journalist looks visibly nervous and uncomfortable. Her facial expressions, limited control of gesture, and awkward reaction to the microphone problem weaken her presence. Therefore, Case 1 is the stronger speech because it is clearer, more professional, and more convincing.
